>
  <p>A drain field only works well when flow is spread across it. The distribution box is what does that spreading — so a small problem there can look like a big field problem.</p>

  {/* Intended asset: /images/resources/septic-distribution-box-problems-hero.webp — see public/images/resources/README.md */}
  <ResourceImageSlot
    src={null}
    alt={"Illustration of a septic distribution box directing flow to drain-field lines, with one line overloaded"}
    width={1600}
    height={900}
  />

  <h2>What Can Go Wrong</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Settling or shifting.</strong> A box that is no longer level can send too much flow to one line.</li>
    <li><strong>Clogging.</strong> Solids or roots can block outlets and unbalance distribution.</li>
    <li><strong>The result.</strong> One part of the field is overloaded while the rest sits idle.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why It Needs Evaluation</h2>
  <p>
    Because the symptoms resemble general field trouble, a provider evaluates to tell them apart — sometimes a box issue is a more contained fix than a field problem. See <a href="/signs-of-drain-field-trouble/">signs of drain-field trouble</a>, or <a href="/request-service/">request septic service</a>.
  </p>

